        "content": "\nThis is the highest-risk gap: all screen-transition and input-handling logic lives here, is pure enough to test directly (no real terminal needed — `tea.KeyMsg` and the custom msg types are plain structs), and currently has zero coverage.\n\n```go\nfunc TestHandleKey_Picking_Navigation(t *testing.T) {\n\tm := newModel(10, \"../crawler\")\n\t// cursor doesn't go below 0\n\tm.handleKey(tea.KeyMsg{Type: tea.KeyRunes, Runes: []rune(\"k\")})\n\tif m.cursor != 0 {\n\t\tt.Errorf(\"cursor should clamp at 0, got %d\", m.cursor)\n\t}\n\t// cursor doesn't exceed len(providers)-1\n\tfor i := 0; i < len(providers)+2; i++ {\n\t\tm.handleKey(tea.KeyMsg{Type: tea.KeyRunes, Runes: []rune(\"j\")})\n\t}\n\tif m.cursor != len(providers)-1 {\n\t\tt.Errorf(\"cursor should clamp at %d, got %d\", len(providers)-1, m.cursor)\n\t}\n}\n\nfunc TestHandleKey_Picking_ToggleAndSelectAll(t *testing.T) {\n\tm := newModel(10, \"../crawler\")\n\tm.handleKey(tea.KeyMsg{Type: tea.KeySpace})\n\tif !m.selected[0] {\n\t\tt.Fatal(\"expected provider 0 selected\")\n\t}\n\tm.handleKey(tea.KeyMsg{Type: tea.KeySpace}) // untested: toggling back off\n\tif m.selected[0] {\n\t\tt.Fatal(\"expected provider 0 deselected\")\n\t}\n\tm.handleKey(tea.KeyMsg{Type: tea.KeyRunes, Runes: []rune(\"a\")})\n\tif m.countSelected() != len(providers) {\n\t\tt.Fatal(\"expected all selected\")\n\t}\n}\n\nfunc TestHandleKey_Enter_NoSelectionSelectsAll(t *testing.T) {\n\tm := newModel(10, \"../crawler\")\n\tm.handleKey(tea.KeyMsg{Type: tea.KeyEnter}) // untested: enter with zero explicit selections\n\tif m.countSelected() != len(providers) {\n\t\tt.Fatal(\"expected implicit select-all on empty selection\")\n\t}\n\tif m.screen != screenLimit {\n\t\tt.Fatal(\"expected transition to screenLimit\")\n\t}\n}\n\nfunc TestHandleKey_Limit_InvalidInputRejected(t *testing.T) {\n\tm := newModel(10, \"../crawler\")\n\tm.screen = screenLimit\n\tm.limitInput.SetValue(\"-5\") // untested: negative limit rejected\n\tm.handleKey(tea.KeyMsg{Type: tea.KeyEnter})\n\tif m.screen != screenLimit {\n\t\tt.Fatal(\"negative limit should not advance screen\")\n\t}\n\tm.limitInput.SetValue(\"abc\") // untested: non-numeric input\n\tm.handleKey(tea.KeyMsg{Type: tea.KeyEnter})\n\tif m.screen != screenLimit {\n\t\tt.Fatal(\"non-numeric limit should not advance screen\")\n\t}\n\tm.limitInput.SetValue(\"0\") // 0 is explicitly valid (\"unlimited\")\n\tm.handleKey(tea.KeyMsg{Type: tea.KeyEnter})\n\tif m.screen != screenRunning {\n\t\tt.Fatal(\"0 should be accepted as valid limit\")\n\t}\n}\n\nfunc TestHandleKey_Limit_EscReturnsToPicking(t *testing.T) {\n\tm := newModel(10, \"../crawler\")\n\tm.screen = screenLimit\n\tm.handleKey(tea.KeyMsg{Type: tea.KeyEsc})\n\tif m.screen != screenPicking {\n\t\tt.Fatal(\"esc should return to picking screen\")\n\t}\n}\n\nfunc TestHandleKey_QuitBlockedWhileRunning(t *testing.T) {\n\tm := newModel(10, \"../crawler\")\n\tm.screen = screenRunning\n\tm.pending = 1\n\t_, cmd := m.handleKey(tea.KeyMsg{Type: tea.KeyRunes, Runes: []rune(\"q\")})\n\tif cmd != nil {\n\t\tt.Fatal(\"q should be a no-op while providers are still pending\") // untested guard\n\t}\n\tm.pending = 0\n\t_, cmd = m.handleKey(tea.KeyMsg{Type: tea.KeyRunes, Runes: []rune(\"q\")})\n\tif cmd == nil {\n\t\tt.Fatal(\"q should quit once pending == 0\")\n\t}\n}\n\nfunc TestUpdate_StatusAndDoneMsg(t *testing.T) {\n\tm := newModel(10, \"../crawler\")\n\tm.runOrder = []string{\"lexpress-mg\"}\n\tm.runCursor = 0\n\tm.statuses[\"lexpress-mg\"] = &providerStatus{state: stateIdle}\n\tm.pending = 1\n\n\tm.Update(statusMsg{provider: \"lexpress-mg\", line: \"fetching...\"})\n\tif m.statuses[\"lexpress-mg\"].state != stateRunning {\n\t\tt.Fatal(\"expected state running after statusMsg\")\n\t}\n\n\tm.Update(doneMsg{provider: \"lexpress-mg\", err: nil})\n\tif m.statuses[\"lexpress-mg\"].state != stateDone || m.pending != 0 {\n\t\tt.Fatal(\"expected done state and pending decremented\")\n\t}\n\n\t// untested: doneMsg with an error sets stateError and appends the error line\n\tm.statuses[\"lexpress-mg\"].state = stateRunning\n\tm.pending = 1\n\tm.Update(doneMsg{provider: \"lexpress-mg\", err: fmt.Errorf(\"boom\")})\n\tif m.statuses[\"lexpress-mg\"].state != stateError {\n\t\tt.Fatal(\"expected stateError on doneMsg with err\")\n\t}\n}\n```\n\n",
        "level": 2
      },
      {
        "title": "3. `runCrawler` / `runHeadless` (main.go:59, 80) — process orchestration, entirely untested and hard to test as written",
        "content": "\nGaps:\n- **No dependency injection** — `runCrawler` hardcodes `exec.Command(\"uv\", \"run\", \"main.py\", ...)`. Can't substitute a fake process without a `PATH` trick.\n- **Untested error paths**: `uv` binary missing (`cmd.Start()` fails), non-zero exit from the crawler, `cmd.Wait()` error after successful start.\n- **Untested `limit=0` behavior**: always passes `--limit 0` literally to the Python side — no test locks in that \"0 means unlimited\" is actually honored end-to-end (this is a Go/Python contract worth a coupling test, or at least a comment-backed unit test asserting the built command args).\n- **Untested scanner edge case**: `bufio.Scanner` has a 64KB default max token size — an unusually long line from the crawler (e.g. huge JSON dump on one line) would make `scanner.Scan()` stop silently with `scanner.Err() == bufio.ErrTooLong`, but that error is **currently swallowed** — `runCrawler` never calls `scanner.Err()`, so a truncated stream looks identical to a clean EOF. This is a real gap, not just missing coverage.\n- **`runHeadless` concurrency**: no test that all providers actually run concurrently or that one provider's error doesn't block/cancel others.\n\nSince `runCrawler` shells out by hardcoded binary name, the practical way to unit-test it is to fake `uv` on `PATH`:\n\n```go\n// main_test.go\nfunc TestRunCrawler_StreamsLinesAndPropagatesExitError(t *testing.T) {\n\tdir := t.TempDir()\n\tfakeUV := filepath.Join(dir, \"uv\")\n\tscript := \"#!/bin/sh\\necho line1\\necho line2 1>&2\\nexit 3\\n\"\n\tif err := os.WriteFile(fakeUV, []byte(script), 0o755); err != nil {\n\t\tt.Fatal(err)\n\t}\n\tt.Setenv(\"PATH\", dir+string(os.PathListSeparator)+os.Getenv(\"PATH\"))\n\n\tvar got []string\n\terr := runCrawler(\"lexpress-mg\", 10, \".\", func(line string) {\n\t\tgot = append(got, line)\n\t})\n\n\tif len(got) != 2 { // untested: stderr folded into same onLine stream as stdout\n\t\tt.Fatalf(\"got %d lines, want 2: %v\", len(got), got)\n\t}\n\tif err == nil {\n\t\tt.Fatal(\"expected non-zero exit to surface as error\") // untested exit-code propagation\n\t}\n}\n\nfunc TestRunCrawler_MissingBinary(t *testing.T) {\n\tt.Setenv(\"PATH\", t.TempDir()) // no `uv` on PATH\n\terr := runCrawler(\"lexpress-mg\", 10, \".\", func(string) {})\n\tif err == nil {\n\t\tt.Fatal(\"expected error when uv binary is missing\") // untested: cmd.Start() failure path\n\t}\n}\n\nfunc TestRunHeadless_AggregatesAllProvidersConcurrently(t *testing.T) {\n\t// same fake-uv-on-PATH technique, invoke runHeadless with 3 names,\n\t// assert stdout (via os.Stdout capture / redirected pipe) contains\n\t// \"[name] line\" for every provider — currently zero coverage that\n\t// runHeadless's fan-out/WaitGroup actually joins all goroutines\n\t// before returning, and that one provider's error doesn't affect others.\n}\n```\n\n",
        "level": 2
      },
      {
        "title": "4. Missing error-handling tests specifically",
        "content": "\n| Path | Current behavior | Test needed |\n|---|---|---|\n| `runCrawler`: `cmd.StdoutPipe()` fails | returns err | not independently testable without mocking `exec.Cmd` — low priority |\n| `runCrawler`: scanner exceeds 64KB line | `scanner.Err()` silently dropped | should assert this is a real gap; recommend checking `scanner.Err()` after the loop and surfacing it |\n| `handleKey` limit parsing: non-numeric / negative / empty string | silently no-ops, stays on screen | covered above — needs test |\n| `main()`: unknown provider name passed via `--providers` | no validation against the `providers` list; falls through to `runHeadless` → `runCrawler`, fails only when the Python side rejects it | worth a validation + test, since currently a typo silently becomes a wasted subprocess spawn with a late, confusing Python-side error |\n| `doneMsg` with error | appends `\"error: \" + err.Error()` to lines, sets `stateError` | covered above |\n\n",
        "level": 2
      },
      {
        "title": "5. Integration test gaps",
        "content": "\n- **No end-to-end test** exercising `main()` itself (flag parsing → headless dispatch) — `main` currently isn't extracted into a testable function; recommend splitting flag-parsing into a small `parseArgs(args []string) (headless bool, providersFlag string, limit int, crawlerDir string)` so it can be tested without `os.Args`/`flag.Parse()` global state.\n- **No full-flow TUI test**: picking screen → limit screen → running screen → all-done, driven purely through `Update()` calls with synthetic `tea.KeyMsg`/`statusMsg`/`doneMsg` sequences (no real terminal needed, since `tea.Program` isn't required to call `Update` directly). This is the most valuable single test to add — it would catch regressions across the whole state machine in one shot.\n- **No coupling test** between the Go `providers` slice (main.go:18) and the Python `PROVIDERS` dict in `apps/crawler/providers.py` — the comment admits these are manually kept in sync (\"11 static strings don't need dynamic coupling\"). Worth at least a `TestProvidersListMatchesCrawlerConfig` that shells out to Python (`uv run python -c \"...\"`) or reads `providers.py` and diffs the two lists, so drift is caught in CI rather than at runtime.\n\n",
        "level": 2
      },
      {
        "title": "Suggested priority order",
        "content": "1. `truncate` (real bug), `handleKey`/`Update` state machine (highest risk surface, zero coverage, cheap to test).\n2. `runCrawler` error paths + the swallowed `scanner.Err()`.\n3. Full-flow TUI integration test.\n4. `main()`/`parseArgs` extraction + provider-list validation.\n5. Go/Python provider-list coupling test.\n\nWant me to actually write these as `main_test.go` / `tui_test.go` files in `apps/cli`, or was this meant to stay a report?",
        "level": 2
      }
